versions of humanness, Animals as Legal Beings seeks to bring critical animal theorizations and animal law closer together. Throughout, Deckha draws upon the feminist animal care tradition, as well as feminist theories of embodiment and relationality, postcolonial theory, and critical animal studies. Her argument is critical of the liberal legal view of animals and directed at a legal subjectivity for animals attentive to their embodied vulnerability, and desirous of an animal-friendly cultural shift in the core foundations of anthropocentric legal systems. Theoretically informed yet accessibly presented, Animals as Legal Beings makes a significant contribution to an array of interdisciplinary debates and is an innovative and astute argument for a meaningful more-than-human turn in law and policy.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aAnimal welfarexLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aAnimal welfarexLaw and legislation. 0aAnimalsxLaw and legislationzCanada. 0aAnimalsxLaw and legislation. 0aFeminism. 7aLAW / General.2bisacsh  aanimals.  aanthropocentrism.  aembodiment.  agender.  alaw.  apersonhood.  aproperty.  arace.  arelationality.  avulnerability.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020z978311069045340uhttps://doi.org/10.3138/978148753824840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781487538248423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781487538248.jpg  a978-3-11-069045-3  University of Toronto Press Complete eBook-Package 2020b2020  aGBV-deGruyter-alles